column169: The cargo has been placed on hold and quarantined. The warehouse manager informed us about a product explosion inside the cargo while it was on the ramp, waiting to be loaded onto the aircraft. column169: The freight was shipped to A. Duie Pyle on poor quality pallets.  The pallet had a nail protruding from it resulting in the unintentional release of 1 liter of corrosive liquid.  Immediate action was taken to mitigate the spill when it was discovered. The damaged jerrican was placed in an overpack container. The clean up materials were placed in a separate overpack container in preparation for disposition.
column170: Ensure the shipper is using good quality pallets that are free of protruding nails that damage freight.  According to our dock supervisor, this is becoming a common issue with chem aqua pallets.

column169: ABF stated that while unloading the commodity they noticed the leaking commodity. ABF stated that it appears to have been forklift while being loaded at is previous location. A crew from TLE arrived on-site. Following a site assessment, TLE personnel noted two (2) pounds of sodium hydroxide was rele ased to the pallet and the concrete surfaces of the loading dock. TLE personnel overpacked the one (1) damaged 500-pound supersack of sodium hydroxide into one (1) 95-gallon overpack as hazardous waste. TLE personnel utilized one (1) HEPA vacuum to collect the released sodium hydroxide from the impa cted surfaces. TLE personnel cut up the impacted pallet as waste. All sodium hydroxide impacted material was collected in one (1) 95-gallon overpack as hazardous waste and staged on-site for further management. TLE personnel noted no further acitons required on-site and crews demobilized.

column169: On June 30, 2205, one (1) 158-gallon tote of UN3082 was punctured in transit and released approximately twenty (20) gallons of product to the trailer interior and dock floor. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from GrayMar Environmental Services (GES) to remediate the site. GES personnel utilized absorbents, cleaners, and hand tools to remediate the impacted site. The contents of the damaged tote were transferred into one (1) new 275-gallon tote. column169: A Veolia employee was unloading a truck from a pick up of waste material from a customer on the previous day when he noticed liquid under a pallet. The drum was inspected and did not show any signs of leaking. The pallet containing the drum was moved off the truck. While moving the drum, it was noticed that a small amount of liquid was dripping from under the closure ring. The drum's ring was missing the closure nut and the closure ring's gasket was compromised.
column170: Veolia employees were reminded to visually inspect drums in preparation for shipment. The closures and integrity of the containers need to be verified as acceptable prior to transportation. Any container exhibiting questionable integrity must not be utilized for shipping hazardous materials. A container's structural integrity and proper closing are fundamental prerequisites for shipping. Comprehensive visual inspections are a mandatory part of the pre-shipment process.

A declared dangerous goods shipment of UN1814, Potassium Hydroxide Solution, Packing Group III was involved in a forklift incident during sort operations at the Federal Express hub in Indianapolis, IN. The outer fiberboard packaging contained two intermediate fiberboard boxes containing two 2L plastic inner containers each. After damaging both the outer and one of the intermediate packagings, one of the plastic inner containers was punctured by the forklift, spilling its entire contents. The product spilled was from Roche Diagnostics, product name “CleanCell M” (part #: 04880293190). The outer box did have proper dangerous goods markings and labeling, and an accurate Shippers Declaration for Dangerous Goods was offered with the shipment. The shipment was placed in a salvage drum for containment and is being held pending further disposition instruction.

At 0424 ET, XPO notified ERTS of a cargo release at UKC. It was reported that approximately 1 gallon of Desmodur 1 was released from one or maybe two 55-gallon DMs due to improper packaging by the shipper. The caller stated that it looks like there is a crack at the bottom of the drum and maybe two drums are damaged. The release impacted trailer #3194091 at dock door 100. ERTS will proceed to dispatch a contractor to the site to complete cleanup activities.  Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 1-gallon of UN2290 Desmodur 1 product was released to the entire area of the wooden due to improper packaging. The contractors cleaned the impacted trailer floor with granular absorbents. The (2) 55-gallon metal drums were overpacked into (2) 85-gallon metal drums and (2) 55-gallon poly drums contain impacted absorbents and pallet pieces. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column169: At 00:52 AM ET, XKC contacted the call center to report a spill that was found inside of a trailer in Kansas City, KS. The spill consists of approximately 25 pounds of Sodium Nitrate Prills, which released from 3–50-pound plastic bags due to not being properly packaged by the shipper, causing them to tear during transit and spill onto the trailer floor.   Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed spill had already been cleaned up by XPO personnel of UN1498 Sodium Nitrate Prills product due to not being properly packaged by shipper. The damaged bags were containerized to an 85-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column169: GROUND HAZMAT PACKAGE DISCOVERED LEAKING
Driver overfilled the customer tank causing an approx. 25 gallons of Clar ION to spill into containment
column170: Before unloading the customer instructed the driver that the tank would be able to hold all of the product.  ¿The driver followed Groendyke’s unloading procedures and reviewed the delivery details with the consignee, including the product, amount, and confirmation that the receiving tank had the capacity for the load. The driver connected the hose and began the delivery, remaining within the required 25-foot monitoring distance. Due to a wall obstructing the view, the driver could not see the tank from the fill line.  During the delivery, he observed product leaking from a hole in the containment area. He immediately shut all valves and notified the consignee. The consignee later confirmed that the tank was already full. They accepted responsibility for the cleanup of approximately 25 gallons of product, some of which had spilled outside the containment area.

Supervisor Peter Kostenko contacted Safety to report a spill on the dock involving UN1133 Adhesives, Class 3, Packing Group II, ERG 128. Peter stated that the container appeared to have been damaged by other freight being moved across the dock floor. He mentioned that he would investigate to identif y the forklift operator responsible for moving the skid into the pail, which caused the spill. Approximately 64 oz of product was spilled from a 5-gallon pail onto the dock floor. Safety advised that CURA would be contacted to assist with the cleanup and disposal of the damaged pail. GES personnel p laced the one (1) damaged 5-gallon pail into one (1) poly liner, and all cleanup debris was collected and containerized into one (1) other poly liner; both poly liners went into one (1) 55-gallon drum that was labeled as hazardous and staged in the terminal's waste holding room. With approval of the  site contact, Peter, crews secured the scene and demobilized.

column169: On 06/26/2025 at approximately 1320, David Terry reported an undeclared dangerous good. The shipment consisted of a plastic container packaged in a fiberboard box. The commodity was identified as acetic acid solution with 99% concentration, and it was not prepared in accordance with DOT HMR Regulations. Per the agent, this shipper has repeatedly attempted to ship this package, which lead to further inspection. The package is being held, pending DOT investigation. The shipper confirmed by provision of the safety data sheet, the shipment is 99% acetic acid.

On June 13, 2025, one (1) 330-gallon tote of UN3264 was forked and released approximately twenty (20) gallons of product to the dock floor. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Hull's Environmental Services (HES) to remediate the impacted site. Crews deployed granular absorbents and soda ash to the release and swept them in with hand tools. All poly aluminum hydroxychloride product was transferred from the damaged 330-gallon tote to a new 330-gallon tote and staged onsite. All spent absorbents were containerized in two 55-gallon drums, and crews cut down the damaged 330-gallon tote and placed that into one (1) 55-gallon drum.

column169: On Wednesday, June 11, 2025, at approximately 1730 hours, a CSXT crew noticed a tank car (UTLX 212517) leaking a liquid substance from the top of the car.  After a call from the CSX Yardmaster at approximately 1733 hours, a Canton employee walked out to inspect the railcar.  It was determined that the leak was coming from the top of the tank car, out of the pressure relief valve, located under the top fitting protection cover.  This leak was due to the car being loaded during the winter months and the product inside the tank expanding due to sunlight warming the side of the tank, causing the contents to expand, thus reducing the available head space in the car.  A Canton Railroad transload employee came out at 1907 hours and pumped 200 gallons out of the car to prevent further dripping out of the safety valve.
column170: Both the shipper and consignee will be notified of the incident and a recommendation will be made to load the railcars, leaving more head room in the tank for expansion of the product during warm weather months.

column43: AMINES, LIQUID, CORROSIVE, N.O.S. OR POLYAMINES, LIQUID, CORROSIVE, N.O.S.
column169: On June 26, 2025, one (1) 55-gallon drum of UN2735 was punctured and released approximately four (4) gallons of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from HazChem Environmental (HCE) to remediate the impacted site. Crews utilized absorbents, soda ash, and hand tools to remediate the impacted trailer floor and containerized the 55-gallon drum of UN2735 product into one (1) 85-gallon overpack.

Two pails arrived crushed from freight shift to 129 from Dallas. One of the pails was empty by the time they arrived. The operations supervisor advised that the pails were creased and did not appear to be damaged from a forklift strike so he was sure it was from the load shift. The operations superv isor also advised that the damaged pails were UN1866. Safety advised CURA would be contacted for remediation. Crews proceeded to unload the trailer, downstack the impacted pallet, and they observed a total two of (2) 5-gallon pails of resin solution (UN1866) had been damaged, so crews removed them f or waste. E3 personnel deployed granular absorbents to the released product in the trailer and swept them in with hand tools. Crews wiped down the impacted freight, pallet, and trailer with absorbent pads and cleaning agents, and restacked the undamaged freight for further shipment and processing. A ll spent absorbents and any miscellaneous cleanup debris were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum, and the damaged pails were all collected and containerized into one (1) other 55-gallon drum. Both drums of waste were labeled appropriately and staged in the terminal's waste holdi ng room.

On June 27, 2025, two (2) 50-gallon drums of UN1993 were damaged by a forklift and released approximately 55-gallons of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Environmental Serivces, Inc. (ESI) to remediate the site.  ESI personnel placed both leaking drums into two (2) 85-gallon overpacks. The crew deployed a degreasing agent to the impacted area and placed granular absorbents on top. Hand tools were utilized to retrieve all loose absorbents and placed them into three (3) 55-gallon drums.

column169: The dock worker was stacking a small pallet on top of another small pallet in front of the drums.  The dock workers fork blades were sticking out and punctured the drum about 1/2 way up the side of the drum.  The dock worker immediately notified leadership which promptly responded to the spill with proper PPE on.  The drum was tipped on its side to stop the leak and placed in an overpack container.  The spilled liquid was neutralized and cleaned up with absorbents.  The absorbents, clean-up materials, and used PPE were placed in separate overpack containers in preparation for disposition.
column170: Retrain the employee on safe handling of and around hazardous materials. Disciplinary action will also be taken against the dock worker responsible for the spill.

column169: ABF Operation Supervisor states that they opened up trailer 552565 in dock door 9 when they found a pallet of UN2880, CALCIUM HYPOCHLORITE, HYDRATED, 5.1, PG II, RQ, CALCIUM that had not been shrink wrapped properly and fell onto another hazmat shipment of UN2014, HYDROGEN PEROXIDE, AQUEOUS SOLUTION S, 5.1 (8), PG II resulting in 5 fl oz of the spill to foam up on the trailer floor. ABF Supervisor states that none of it hit the yard. ABF Supervisor states that the freight had also not been properly blocked or braced for the UN2880 hazmat pallet which is what resulted in the spill to occur. ABF Supervisor states that a really small amount of both hazmats did make contact but a majority of it was still sealed. Safety advised supervisor to block the spill off from it spreading additionally until CURA arrived on-site to clean it. Safety contacted CURA and they're dispatch someone on emergency  response for cleanup.
column170: Proper bracing of the freight would've stopped this spill from occurring.

column169: Incident Report: Transportation Package Failure and Release Response Sequence of Events Leading to the Incident: On the morning of June 16, 2025, at 8:26 AM, Driver Carnest Nutall contacted dispatch to report that he had run his truck and trailer off the road and into a ditch at the curve where County Road 174 intersects Bob Wilson Road, while traveling northbound. The unit involved was Truck RC-34 pulling Trailer 107, both loaded with chemical product identified under BOL 1150607. The material being transported was M2Guard-HSR105G, manufactured by Foremark Performance for M2 Chemical. The driver was approximately 15 minutes from the delivery location at the time of the incident. Driver Nutall reported that he was unable to stop the truck and trailer due to apparent brake failure. The posted speed limit for the curve was 15 mph, as confirmed by photographs taken at the scene, which also documented tire marks showing the vehicle sliding off the road and rolling. Actions Taken at the Time of Discovery: The driver immediately notified dispatch and confirmed that he had sustained injuries to his head and lower back, but no other vehicles or individuals were involved. Local law enforcement was notified, and Officer Cliff Lance (Phone: 318-426-499) responded to the scene. The Louisiana State Police accident hotline was contacted at 10:19 AM; the call was taken by Amanda, who provided Incident #2121, which was initially given by Officer Lance. E3 Environmental was contacted to oversee environmental remediation and cleanup. They will be providing a cost estimate and handling hazardous materials containment. Nolan's Towing was notified to upright the truck and trailer and coordinate safe offloading of the contents. A secondary trailer, TX-18, operated by Driver Alan Reeves, was dispatched to receive the chemical transfer from the damaged trailer. Description of Package Failure: • The trailer was fully loaded with 45k of M2Guard-HSR105G at the time of the accident. Due to the trailer rolling into a ditch, there is potential for container displacement or compromise, though a full damage assessment was pending at time of report. While no visible punctures, cracks, or leaks were initially confirmed via driver call, an on-site inspection was ordered noticed some seepage from washout cap on dome lid area. Photographs taken at the scene showed clear evidence of road departure, slide marks, and the overturned position of the truck and trailer. • Any cracked, punctured, or ruptured drums will be identified by E3 Environmental and reported under separate documentation. Estimated Duration of Release: The exact duration of any material release is currently unknown pending E3's assessment. However, based on the time of the call (8:26 AM) and environmental response initiation (around 12:30 PM). Scene secured by law enforcement to prevent unauthorized access or ignition hazards. When Driver returned to facility and was getting ready to unload he opened the doors and noticed that the floor was wet and material began dripping from the back of the trailer onto the pavement @1500ct. The driver then notified his manager and absorbents were set down to collect any free liquid. The internal response team was called to address the clean-up. They collected the materials needed to address the clean up and began transferring the material to another tote @1600ct. While transferring the material they laid more absorbents down to collect and begin cleaning up the material that had gotten on the pavement and the floor of the trailer. Approximately 10-15 gallons was released. Once the damaged tote was emptied they cut it up and repackaged it for disposal. The clean up was complete @1945ct.
column170: When reviewing the information it was discovered that the tote was sitting outside at the customers location in the sun causing damage to the plastic. The plastic had gotten brittle in the sun and when transporting the plastic cracked allowing the material to be release. The situation was discussed with the employee and retraining was issued on container integrity and closure procedures.

column169: At 1836 ET, XPO, notified ERTS of a cargo release at XPN. It was reported that approximately 3 gallons of Potassium Hydroxide Solution released from a plastic pail due to improper loading by the shipper. The release impacted trailer # 4630542 and the concrete at the head of the trailer outside. ERTS will proceed to dispatch a contractor to the site to complete cleanup activities.   Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 5-gallons of UN1814 Potassium Hydroxide Solution product released to 10’x5’ area of the wooden trailer floor and concrete due to improper loading. The impacted areas of the floor were treated with sodium bicarb and generated (2) 55-poly drums containing damaged product, rags,  absorbents and PPE. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column169: On June 19, 2025, one (1) 275-gallon tote of UN1760 was punctured and released approximately 135-gallons of product to the trailer interior and pavement. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Hull's Environmental Services (HES) to remediate the site. HES personnel deployed neutralizing, granular absorbents to the released product, worked them in, and collected the spent absorbents with hand tools. The contents of the damaged tote were transferred into one (1) new 275-gallon tote. The damaged tote was cut up for waste. All impacted materials were containerized in six (6) 55-gallon drums.

On 6/30/2025, free liquid was observed in the secondary containment for the bushings. The secondary containment ended up failing and suspected PCB oil (>500 ppm) leaked from secondary containment onto the trailer flooring. The spilled material was fully contained within the trailer. It is estimated that 2 gallons of suspected PCB oil was leaked out of the secondary containment. Absorbent material was placed on the leak as well as within the secondary containment. All absorbent material that was used to clean the spill outside the secondary containment was placed back within the containment.
column170: This incident is still under investigation on how the secondary containment failed. The secondary containment is being evaluated for improvements.

column169: Hepaco was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted a 2ft-by-2ft area of the concrete dock floor and estimated that twenty-five (25) gallons of material were released due to a puncture in one (1) 330-gallon poly tote. Hepaco personnel began the tote transfer and transferred eight hundred (800) liters of material. The damaged tote was cut up and placed into poly containers. The contaminated area was decontaminated, neutralized, and cleaned. The generated waste consists of five (5) 55-gallon poly drums containing impacted debris, absorbents, and cut-up tote pieces. All waste was staged onsite at bay 34. The contractor checked out with ESTES terminal employee Shane Smith. The generated waste will remain onsite for the ESTES DGRM team to coordinate disposal.

column169: On 02/25/2025 at approximately 0645, Dangerous Goods Administration received notification from operations staff at the ramp facility in Greer, SC that the outer packaging of a shipment containing a declared Class 3 dangerous goods commodity was observed to be damp. The shipment consisted of one outer fiberboard box that contained one inner plastic bottle. Initially, the shipment was reported as sustaining outer package damage only with the damp outer packaging believed to result from an unknown external substance.  However, when arranging for final disposition of the package on 6/5/2025, a visible tear in the tape used to secure the top onto the lid observed that had not been previously documented, changing the determination that the initial reported damp outer packaging. may have resulted from a small amount of leakage from the cap inner bottle.

column43: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column169: On June 13, 2025, one (1) 3,000-pound tote of sulfuric acid was damaged by an explosion inside the tote and released approximately two hundred (200) gallons of product to the trailer interior and terminal yard. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from EnviroServe (ES) to remediate the site. ES personnel deployed soda ash to the trailer interior, pavement and tires of nearby trailers. All sulfuric acid impacted material was collected and containerized into fifteen (15) 55-gallon drums and eleven (11) 35-gallon drums for future terminal disposal.

On June 25, 2025, around 17:05 pm, a severe weather event caused a van trailer parked at Veolia's 10 Day in-transit facility to tip over. The impact of the trailer hitting the ground led to some containers being thrown and colliding with the opposite wall of the trailer. This collision resulted in damage to the container lids and a small amount of material being spilled. After the weather improved, the van trailer was righted and the containers and spilled material were inspected. 4 out of 7 containers suffered with cracked lids and were overpacked into 551H2 containers.
column170: The Veolia site will review its current operations to determine if enhancements could help prevent inclement weather events in the future such as being weather aware and moving trailers to a safer area, if available.

column169: At 19:01 PM ET, XEL contacted the call center to request help with a spill that was discovered inside of a trailer in Milan, OH. The spill potentially consists of multiple class 8 corrosive liquids, as the trailer was opened and they discovered liquid pouring all over the trailer floor and onto the ground beneath it as well.   Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 2-gallons of UN1760 Direct Plus Acid Sanitizer to area of the wooden trailer floor due to freight shifting and crushing the pail. The damaged pail and product were containerized into a 55-gallon poly drum, the impacted and neutralized absorbents, PPE and debris was containerized into a 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column169: At 07:38 EST, ERTS was contacted by XPO (XSJ) about a cargo release. It was reported that due to a forklift incident, an unknown amount of 3M Furnace Black Acrylic Paint (hazardous - UN1993) was released. The caller stated that the released product was contained to the trailer floor. The terminal has requested a contractor out for cleanup and containment due to the size and type spill. There were no drains, soils or waterways reported to have been impacted by the release.   Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 5-gallons UN1993 3M Furnace Black Acrylic Paint product released to wooden trailer floor due to forklift puncture. The contractors used paint thinner, hotsy and regular pressure washer on the trailer floor. The waste was containerized into 55-gallon metal drum contains product, absorbent pads and trash from trailer floor, (1) 55-gallon metal drum contains wash water, product and paint thinner. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column169: Clean Harbors was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted a 600ft-by-1ft area of concrete between the trailer and soil and a 5ft-by-5ft area of soil and estimated that fifty-five (55) gallons of material was released from one (1) 55-gallon poly drum due to the drum being forked. Before the contractor arrived, the facility personnel placed the leaking drum into one (1) 95-gallon steel drum with the top cut off that already contained other absorbent materials. Clean Harbors personnel deployed granular absorbents and a neutralizer to the affected areas. It was determined that a strip of one foot away along the concrete was going to need to be excavated. Seven (7) 55-gallon poly drums of contaminated soil and impacted absorbents were generated. The drums began bulging and it was advised that containment will need to be established around the drums, and they will need to be left outside to vent. The lids were loosened and covered with poly sheeting. The waste was staged onsite before contractor demobilization. The generated waste will remain onsite for the ESTES DGRM team to coordinate disposal.

column43: LITHIUM ION BATTERIES INCLUDING LITHIUM ION POLYMER BATTERIES
column169: A passenger on one of our flights had a personal spare battery go into thermal runaway in flight. The battery wrapped in a sweater. The flight was from Winnipeg, CA (YWG) to Chicago, O’Hare (ORD) scheduled departure time 14:20 hours. The crew reported that there was no detectable smoke or fire, but the battery was very hot, and the external case had split. Duration time was short.  The battery was placed in the on-board fire containment bag and submerged in water without further incident. There were no reported crew or passenger injuries. The National Response Center was notified.
column170: The battery was contained without any damage or injury. the exact specifications of the battery are unknown as it was disposed of.

Vehicle owned by Pilot Travel Centers LLC (PTC) was exiting I-283 onto I-83N, when another vehicle made a sudden lane change from the left and struck the PTC tractor.  The contact caused the PTC driver to lose control of the vehicle and the vehicle subsequently struck a gaurd rail and overturned.  As a result, the trailer shell was breached and approximately 4000 gallons of diesel fuel were released.  Video of event was captured by in-cab cameras equipped on PTC vehicle.
column170: There is nothing our driver could have done to prevent the release.

DECLARED LEAKING GROUND HAZMAT. SPILL CLEANED UP USING COMPANY PROCEDURES.

t 20:28 PM ET, with BCH contacted the call center to report a spill that occurred inside of a trailer in Chicago Heights, IL. The spill consists of approximately half a gallon of Zep Industrial Purple Degreaser & Cleaner, which was released from 4-1-gallon plastic jugs due to other freight being double stacked on top of the containers, crushing them and spilling onto the trailer floor. ERTS will dispatch a contractor to assist, as this is a corrosive material.   Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately .5-gallon of UN3266 Zep products released to a 1’x1’ area of the wooden trailer floor due to improper loading. The contractors cleaned and neutralized with Simple Green and oil dry. The (2) bottles of Zep Industrial Purple Degreaser & Cleaner were placed in 55-gallon poly drum, (3) bottles of Zep Neutral pH Floor Cleaner were placed in 55-gallon poly drum, (4) bottles of Zep All Purpose Cleaner were placed in 55-gallon poly drum, (3) bottles of Zep House and Siding Pressure wash were  placed in a 55-gallon poly drum. The impacted oil dry and PPE were containerized to a 55-gallon poly  drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column169: At 20:45 PM ET, XSL contacted the call center to report a spill that was found inside a trailer in St. Louis, MO. The spill consists of two separate products: 4-1-gallon metal pails of GC Epoxy Primer Red Part A, and 1-5-gallon metal bucket of Pumadeq Flex 31MV White, which were not packaged properly and came loose during transit, spilling 5 ounces each onto the trailer floor. ERTS reviewed the SDS with the terminal, who stated they will clean the spills and place the GC Epoxy containers into a (1) 30-gallon plastic drum, and the Pumadeq will be placed into a separate 30 gallon plastic drum.
attachment Name:Hazmat- Damaged Haz Mat Package Disposition 04302024.pdf

At 0937 EST, XPO notified ERTS of a cargo release at terminal XRY. It was reported that approximately 2) 1 gallon poly jugs of Aqua Balance UN1789 Hydrochloric acid, solution released due to forklift puncture. The release impacted trailer # 4653789. ERTS will proceed to dispatch a contractor to the site to complete cleanup activities.  Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 2-gallons of UN1789 Aqua Balance Muriatic Acid product released to the wooden trailer floor due to forklift puncture. The impacted areas of the floor were treated with the Kolor Safe Acid Neutralizer and generated (3) 85-poly drums containing damaged product, rags, absorbents and PPE. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

At 0358 EDT on 6/7, XPO-UDV contacted ERTS to report a spill of about 8 gallons of "AQUANOMIC 2.0 LOW TEMP LAUNDRY BUILDER" from a 15-gallon poly drum onto the trailer floor. The drum was punctured due to poor loading by LDA. The material is a class 8 corrosive, and ERTS will dispatch a contractor to assist with the spill.  Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 20-gallons of UN1824 Aquanomic 2.0 Low Temp Laundry Builder product released to an area of the wooden trailer floor and concrete dock floor due to a puncture from forklift or damaged pallet while in transit. The crew used granular absorbents to clean the impacted area and overpacked the damaged pails into (2) 55-gallon poly drums, (3) 55-gallon poly drums contains impacted absorbents, 55-gallon poly drum contains contaminated PPE. The waste was staged onsite for terminal to manage.

column169: On 06/26/2025 at approximately 1049, David Terry reported an undeclared dangerous good. The shipment consisted of a plastic container packaged in a fiberboard box. Per the agent, this shipper has repeatedly attempted to ship this package, which lead to further inspection. The package is being held, pending DOT investigation. The shipper confirmed by provision of the safety data sheet, the shipment is not less than 50% acid, and is over the 1 liter limited quantity.

column169: On June 25, 2025, one (1) 55-gallon drum of Hydrochloric Acid was forked and released approximately three (3) gallons of product to the trailer interior and concrete below. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Response Management Services (RMS) to remediate the site. RMS personnel deployed an acid neutralizer mix and worked in with hand tools. All Hydrochloric Acid-20 Baume-impacted material was collected and containerized in one (1) 55-gallon poly drum for transport and disposal, and the punctured drum was placed in one (1) 95-gallon overpack for further transport.

On June 3, 2025, one (1) 55-gallon drum of sodium hydroxide solution fell over in transit due to improper securement and released approximately four (4) ounces of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Environmental Restoration (ER) to remediate the impacted site. The crew utilized absorbent pads and cleaning agents to wipe down the drum and impacted floor. ER personnel then replaced the bung on the drum and staged it onsite for further processing. All impacted materials were containerized in one (1) 5-gallon pail for future disposal.

column169: On 6/7/2025 at 20:43 hour, personnel in the CSXT Cumberland Yard reported PROX 44177, a residue tank car of Petroleum Distillates NOS, leaking from the top area of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Centennial Energy, was notified via CHEMTREC Report # 2025-0613-00. SPSI, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the car to leaking vapors due to a faulty vacuum relief valve.  Contractor personnel removed the faulty vacuum relief valve and installed a blind closure to stop the product release. The car was held pending further repair by a certified shop or OTMA.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper’s representative- Brian Newcome (303-597-5678).

column169: At 0155 ET, XPO notified ERTS of a cargo release at BIN. It was reported that approximately 2 ounces of Unisol Liquid Red BK-50 released from a 355-gallon metal tote due to the seal at the top of the tote being damaged (see photos). The release impacted tote/concrete. ERTS will proceed to dispatch a Scheduled contractor to the site to complete cleanup activities.  Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 1-ounce of UN1993 Unisol Liquid Rd BK-50 product released to a 4’ x 4’ area impacting the top and sides of the metal tote due to broken gasket/improper packaging. A new gasket was requested with the shipper which was received and replaced. The contractors performed the slosh test and cleaned the outside of the tote.

column169: At 0028 ET, XPO notified ERTS of a cargo release at BCH. It was reported that approximately 5 gallons of battery acid released from a 2105-pound commercial battery due to improper loading and blocking and bracing by terminal BGB. The release impacted trailer # 3233736 and the concrete under the trailer at dock door 136. Absorbents and noodles have been placed to prevent migration to the drains. Mike stated that Dion with Clean Harbors already agreed to assist with the cleanup.   Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 10-gallons of UN2794 Battery Acid released to the wooden trailer floor and concrete dock floor due to improper loading / blocking & bracing. The contractors cleaned and neutralized the trailer floor and concrete dock floor and transferred the products to new pallets. The waste was containerized to (4) 55-gallon poly drums with battery acid and impacted soda ash and (1) 275-gallon tote with battery acid and impacted rinse water. The 2100-pound battery was placed on a skid. The  waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column169: Truck Driver 1169 reported container GESU672757-9 leaking after driver had stopped at a TA Travel Center (2112 FL-71, Mariana, FL 32448) to fuel. The container was confirmed to be carrying 18 IBC totes of (UN1760, CORROSIVE LIQUID, N.O.S. (AMMONIUM HYDROXIDE, SODIUM HYDROXIDE), CLASS 8, PG II), loaded and sealed by shipper Cytec Industries Technology Solutions at their warehouse, and picked up by driver 1169 earlier that day. Following the initial report, the container was moved to an isolated area of the truck stop, and 911 was contacted. Jackson County police and fire departments responded to the scene; fire department proceeded to cut the seal and enter the container to assess the situation. A.C.T. Environmental was contracted to respond and provide clean-up and disposal services, arriving onsite at approximately 1900 and completing the clean-up at approximately 0600 the following morning (6/19/25). The leak was confirmed to come from one of the IBCs which appeared to have been punctured by a sharp object (potentially a forklift during loading) on one of the sides near the bottom of the IBC.

At 16:09 ET, XPO notified the Call Center of a cargo release at a customer location in Lampasas, TX. It was reported that approximately 6 gallons of Acid Magic Multi-Use Formula released from one 275-gallon tote due to unknown reasons. The release impacted trailer #4355071. No storm drains or waterways are reported to be impacted by the release.   Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 15-gallons of UN1760 Acid Magic Multi-Use Formula product released to entire wooden trailer floor and 15’x4’ gravel area due to punctured by other freight. The tote was transferred and then cut up and put in (3) 55-gallon poly drums containing impacted debris, PPE and cut-up tote pieces. The waste was taken to the terminal and staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

On June 15th 2025, Ingenium experienced a trailer fire while transporting hazardous waste eastbound on Interstate 90. The incident occurred on the off-ramp at mile marker 191, temporarily blocking access. The fire originated in the rear section of the trailer.  According to the driver’s report, the incident began with a tire blowout, followed by a second blowout on the rear axle. The Automatic Valve System (AVS) failed to engage; likely due to damage from debris or the tire failure, causing the brakes to lock and overheat. This overheating generated sparks that are believed to have ignited the underside of the trailer.  Ingenium contacted and reported the incident to NRC (NRC# 1434197) when immediately available to do so.  The fire resulted in the partial destruction of manifested hazardous waste. Emergency responders, including the Murdo Volunteer Fire Department and Murdo Police Department, were immediately dispatched. Ingenium coordinated with its emergency response contractor, Ambipar (North Dakota), and worked alongside local and state authorities to secure the scene and begin cleanup operations.  Initial field assessments indicate that the majority of the damage occurred in the rear section of the trailer, which contained waste associated with Systech manifests. While many containers remained intact, all materials were transferred to new containers or salvage drums as a precaution.  Due to the extent of the incident, the waste shipments could not be delivered to the originally designated facilities (TSDFs) as planned. A portion of the waste was destroyed in the fire. The remaining materials were recovered, secured, and segregated for proper management. These recovered materials were subsequently shipped to an alternate permitted facility for identification, profiling, and compliant handling.  All recovered waste is being managed under EPA ID SDR000222927 (Ingenium Group, LLC) in accordance with Episodic Event reporting protocols, as the materials are now considered commingled with other manifested waste from the same trailer.  Regulatory notifications were submitted to: Oregon DEQ Hazardous Waste Program Washington State Department of Ecology  Impacted manifest numbers include: 000554545DAT, 000554550DAT, 000554552DAT, 000554555DAT, 000556777DAT, 000554526DAT, 000554528DAT, 000554537DAT, 000554540DAT, 000554544DAT, 000554548DAT, 000554551DAT, 000554553DAT, 000554556DAT, 000554573DAT, 000554583DAT, 000556767DAT, 000556769DAT, 000556775DAT, and 000556782DAT.  EPA Waste Codes Involved: D001, D002, D004–D008, D010, D011, D035, F003, F005.  Ingenium assumed full ownership of all hazardous materials on the trailer and subsequently obtained a temporary EPA Site ID for the fire location to facilitate proper management and reporting.  Per the South Dakota Department of Agriculture, Ingenium conducted excavation of areas potentially impacted by runoff from firefighting activities. These areas will be backfilled with clean fill and reseeded. Analytica
column170: Look at possible fire prevention materials under trailers.  Investigate previously annual preventative maintenance records and service claims.

All recovered waste is being managed under EPA ID SDR000222927 (Ingenium Group, LLC) in accordance with Episodic Event reporting protocols, as the materials are now considered commingled with other manifested waste from the same trailer.  Regulatory notifications were submitted to: Oregon DEQ Hazardous Waste Program Washington State Department of Ecology  Impacted manifest numbers include: 000554545DAT, 000554550DAT, 000554552DAT, 000554555DAT, 000556777DAT, 000554526DAT, 000554528DAT, 000554537DAT, 000554540DAT, 000554544DAT, 000554548DAT, 000554551DAT, 000554553DAT, 000554556DAT, 000554573DAT, 000554583DAT, 000556767DAT, 000556769DAT, 000556775DAT, and 000556782DAT.  EPA Waste Codes Involved: D001, D002, D004–D008, D010, D011, D035, F003, F005.  Ingenium assumed full ownership of all hazardous materials on the trailer and subsequently obtained a temporary EPA Site ID for the fire location to facilitate proper management and reporting.  Per the South Dakota Department of Agriculture, Ingenium conducted excavation of areas potentially impacted by runoff from firefighting activities. These areas will be backfilled with clean fill and reseeded. Analytica

column169: Dayton Freight personnel observed approximately five (5) gallons of material released from one (1) 5-gallon plastic pail due to a nail that resulted in the pail being punctured after a load shift. The released material impacted the trailer floor. Dayton Freight personnel deployed granular absorbents to the impacted area and gathered the spent material and containerized it into one (1) 5-gallon poly drum. One (1) 55-gallon poly drum was used to containerize the damaged pail. The generated waste was staged onsite at the terminal in a secure location. The generated waste will remain onsite for Dayton Freight’s contracted hazardous waste vendor to coordinate disposal.

column43: LITHIUM ION BATTERIES INCLUDING LITHIUM ION POLYMER BATTERIES
column169: AT THE UPS LATHROP CALIFORNIA FACILITY, A THERMAL BATTERY EVENT OCCURRED WITH ONE AIR PACKAGE CONTAINING LITHIUM ION BATTERIES. IT WAS REPORTED THAT CONTENTS OF A PACKAGE EXPLODED INSIDE FEEDER TRAILER 180646 DURING THE TRAILER UNLOAD.THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO THE EVENT.AN OUTSIDE RESPONDER CLEANED UP THE DEBRIS PLACING PACKAGE AND ALL CONTENTS IN A 55-GALLON DRUM FOR DISPOSAL. THE PACKAGE CONTAINED THIRTY CYLINDRICAL SHAPED RECHARGEABLE LITHIUM-ION BATTERY CELLS, RATED AT 116.4 WATT HOUR PER CELL. THE OUTER BOX WAS APPROPRIATELY MARKED AND LABELLED WITH APPLIED DANGEROUS GOODS SHIPPING PAPERS. THE PACKAGE WAS OFFERED AIR SERVICE AND HAD PASSED AN ACCEPTANCE AUDIT AT THE ORIGIN FACILITY PRIOR TO THE THERMAL EVENT. THE PACKAGE WAS NOT TRANSPORTED IN THE AIR NETWORK. A REPORT WAS MADE TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER ON 01-JULY-2025, NRC REPORT 1435714. THE PACKAGE WAS SHIPPED FROM CALIFORNIA USING UPS ACCOUNT 55R5E9, RIVIAN AUTOMOTIVE LLC, 41100 PLYMOUTH RD, PLYMOUTH MI 48170.

column169: Clean Harbors was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted a 6ft-by-6ft area of the trailer floor and concrete floor and estimated that five (5) gallons of material were released due to unknown reasons from one (1) 55-gallon metal drum. Clean Harbors personnel had a technician bring out SCBA gear for the clean-up. Absorbent pads were applied to the affected areas and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon poly drum. The damaged drum was overpacked into one (1) 65-gallon poly overpack. The generated waste was staged onsite at the terminal prior to the contractor demobilization. The generated waste will remain onsite for the ESTES DGRM team to coordinate disposal.

Freight handler went to lift a tote with another tote right behind it, as he entered the blades it cut the tote behind the one he was picking up and puncturing it. It punctured the body of the poly tote. Hazmat One was called out for clean up and containing spill.

column169: At approximately 7:15AM Central on 6/24/2025, FedEx Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from destination station in Dallas, TX for a dangerous goods spill with tracking 882234574549.  The package had multiple containers and was declared as an All Packed in One fibreboard box containing UN1263 Paint Related Material and UN3470 Paint Related Material, Corrosive, Flammable.  The specific product that spilled was CAAPCOAT PUT-10 Polyurethane Thinner, which the SDS confirmed was the UN1263 Paint Related Material.  A single 1L glass container spilled from a broken closure of the bottle, spilling about 75mL of liquid..  The spill was contained by the dangerous goods spill cleanup specialist and held for pickup by the recipient.

At 0214 ET, XPO notified ERTS of a cargo release at terminal BNA. It was reported that approximately 8-oz of "Provox C (Sodium Carbonate Peroxhydrate)" released from a paper bag due to improper handling. ERTS reviewed the SDS with the caller and determined that terminal personnel are not capable of cleaning the release with PPE available on site.   Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 5-ounces of UN3378 Provox C product released to the concrete dock floor due to improper loading. The contractors collected all released material and containerized product into a 30-gallon poly drum and placed impacted PPE and contaminated product into a 30-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column169: On 06/09/2025 at approximately 2055, Dangerous Goods Administration received notification of a lithium battery fire.  The shipment consisted of one fiberboard box that appeared to contain 2 lithium batteries.  During sort operations, the shipment began to smoke.  The package was extinguished and submerged in water to neutralize the heat.  Further investigation revealed that the battery shipment was not prepared in accordance with IATA regulations, missing the required markings, labeling, packaging and paperwork, deeming it undeclared dangerous goods.  The package is being held, pending an investigation by the FAA.

A trailer arrived to 063 and while it was being unloaded, it was discovered that two boxes containing jugs on the trailer was crushed and one of the jugs had leaked onto the trailer floor.  FCE crew donned the appropriate PPE and identified the estimated six (6) gallon release of potassium hydroxide  (UN1814) on the trailer floor. FCE personnel downstacked the pallet and removed eight (8) damaged 1-gallon jugs of product from the load. Crews deployed neutralizing granular absorbents to collect the released product, swept them up, then proceeded to wipe down any impacted surfaces and undamaged f reight with absorbent pads and cleaning agents. All undamaged freight was restacked for further shipment and processing. One (1) 55-gallon drum that contained the impacted jugs, and one (1) 55-gallon drum that contained the spent absorbents and any miscellaneous cleanup debris were generated as wast e and staged in the terminal's waste holding room.

On June 26, 2025, one (1) 55-gallon drum of UN1212 was punctured and released approximately 55-gallons of product to the trailer interior and concrete beneath. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Carolina Environmental Response Team (CERT) to remediate the site. CERT personnel utilized hand tools, absorbents, and a vacuum unit to remediate the UN1212-impacted site. The damaged drum was placed into one (1) 95-gallon overpack and the impacted material and absorbents were collected and containerized into three (3) 55-gallon drums.

column169: While offloading a truck at Veolia's 10 day intransit facility in Dayton, OH, a Veolia employee noticed a small spot on the truck bed. Upon further inspection, the employee discovered a drum that had two small pin holes approximately a 1/3 of the way down the drum. The drum was immediately overpacked and the small spill was cleaned up.
column170: Veolia employees were reminded to visually inspect all drums in preparation for transportation. The integrity of the containers need to be verified and acceptable for for shipment. Any container exhibiting questionable integrity must not be utilized for shipping hazardous materials. A container's structural integrity and proper sealing are fundamental prerequisites for shipping. Comprehensive visual inspections are a mandatory part of the pre-shipment process. Containers not meeting these requirements shall be overpacked, or not accepted for shipment.

column169: At 1831 EDT on 6/9, XPO-BNA contacted ERTS to report a spill of about 2 cups of Lead Battery Acid from 4x 80lb batteries on a trailer. The batteries were improperly loaded and damaged at BNA. ERTS reviewed the SDS with the caller, and although the terminal can clean the spill, the caller stated that their SCM, Dana Boles, had approved their request for contractor assistance.  Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 2-cups of UN2794 Lead Battery Acid product released to a 4’x4’ area of the wooden trailer floor, steel grate on trailer floor and concrete beneath trailer due to improper loading. The contractors overpacked the battery into a 30-gallon poly drum and impacted absorbents were placed  into 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column169: Operations Supervisor I Jonathan Santos contacted safety to report a Hazardous Spill. Jonathan stated trailer 571577 was on the string pad in the 042/CAR yard when they noticed that it was leaking. Jonathan stated they attempted to open the door and roughly 6-gallons leaked out of the trailer and on to the yard. Jonathan stated he closed the door to keep the spill from getting worse on the yard. Jonathan stated two PROs were loaded onto trailer 571577, PRO 352225899 and PRO 051871342. PRO 352225899 was (30) 55-gallon drums of UN1866, Resin Solution, Flammable, 3, PG III and PRO 051871342 was (1 0) 1,200-lb Gaylords of flakes NOI, Granules, Lumps, Pellets, powder or Solid Mass, CL 60. It was determined that PRO 352225899 was leaking inside the trailer and onto the trailer floor. Jonathan stated that he was unsure the cause of the spill quantity that spilled. Jonathan stated that the trailer  was loaded on 06/1/2025 at 13:24 (EST) at Dock Door 143. Jonathan stated that he did not see any spillage on the yard outside dock door 143 but he did see spillage on the 610 spot were it was staged before it was moved to the string pad. No storm drains or waterways were reported impacted by the re lease. Safety contacted CURA and spoke with Reagan Cowdrey for remediation. Safety requested that CURA provide the cause of the spillage and the spilled quantity. *ggattis* The cleanup crew stated the drum was punctured by a forklift while loading.

column169: At 10:06 ET, XPO notified the Call Center of a cargo release and tote transfer at terminal XID. It was reported that approximately 10 gallons of Trimec 992 released from one 275-gallon tote due to a forklift puncture. The release occurred on dock #12. No storm drains or waterways are reported to be impacted by the release.   Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 60-gallon UN3082 Trimec 992 product released to 6’x’6’ are of the concrete dock floor due to forklift puncture. The remaining contents of the product was transferred to a new tote. The old tote was cut-up and put into flex bin for disposal. There were some pallets which were impacted which were cleaned and wiped down. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column169: Dayton Freight personnel observed approximately one (1) ounce of material released from one (1) 5-gallon metal pail due to improperly loaded freight that resulted in the top of the pail popping off and leaking. The released material impacted only the top of the container. The damaged container with product was containerized into one (1) 10-gallon metal drum. The generated waste was staged onsite at the terminal in a secure location. The generated waste will remain onsite for Dayton Freight’s contracted hazardous waste vendor to coordinate disposal.

The shipment consisted of 3 different containers containing paint and one container holding a corrosive substance.  The package showed signs of spillage on the outside.  Further inspection revealed that one of the paint containers leaked inside of the package, resulting in spillage onto the other containers in the package.  The shipment was not prepared in accordance with IATA regulations, missing the required markings, labeling, packaging and paperwork.  The package is being held, pending an investigation by the FAA.

The shipper advised the cargo was non-haz lead cans. Because its overpack crate broke in the ocean container from China to the U.S., our Chicago CFS discovered a package with a class 7 label and UN3332 markings. After speaking to the consignee we learned this classification was incorrect. The package was now classified as EMPTY and was UN2908. It was being returned to them because they are the manufacturer. They advised us how to correctly label and mark the package before they had it picked up.
column170: We advised our Shanghai office to watch for future shipments from this shipper or future shipments to the same consignee as it most likely will be radioactive. Vanguard Logistics Services prohibits all class 7 shipments.

column169: Punctured by a forklift blade strike.

On June 5, 2025, four (4) 55-gallon drums of Hurricane (UN2922) fell off the lift gate and released approximately 80-gallons of product to the ground and storm drain. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Patriot Environmental Services (PES) to remediate the site. The crew utilized granular absorbents, an absorbent boom, degreasing agent, and a pressure washer to remediate the site. All rinsate was containerized in three (3) 55-gallon drums. One (1) emptied drum was containerized in one (1) 95-gallon overpack for disposal. The crew had to return to the site to at a later date to gain access to the impacted storm drain.   On June 11, 2025, crews returned to the site. The outflow from catch basin was dammed with absorbent boom. Vacuum truck was mobilized to the outlet of the drainage pipe in preparation for collection during flushing activities. One (1) jet vacuum was utilized to flush the drain line pipe and all impacted rinsate was collected and containerized into one (1) vacuum truck for disposal.

Veolia's repack supervisor went to pull in trailer #190165, from a 10-day intransit site that had arrived on June 24. When they opened the doors they noticed that the load was not secured, upon entering the trailer there was a pallet with 5 gallon carboy containers. The containers were not stretched wrapped to the pallet and had fallen over during transportation which caused a container to leak. The trailer was offloaded and inspected to ensure there were no additional containers leaking. There was approximately 2 gallons of UN 1197 Flavoring liquid released. The material was cleaned up, all leaked material stayed in secondary containment and no injuries were reported.

column169: On June 18, 2025, one (1) 55-gallon drum of UN1993 was forked and released approximately ten (10) gallons of product to the trailer interior and pavement beneath. column169: The forklift operator was unloading the trailer when he punctured the drum with his fork blades.  Printing ink began to leak from the hole. The dock worker immediately notified hazwoper trained personnel to assist.  Recovery drums were placed outside of the trailer to capture anything that may leak out. Boom was also placed in the area to contain any spilled material that missed the recovery drums. Absorbents were placed anywhere ink was spilled to absorb it. The damaged drum and spill clean up materials were placed inside of separate overpack drums in preparation for disposition.
column170: Retraining of the dockworker on safe forklift operation near hazardous materials. The dock worker will also face disciplinary action for the spill.

column169: On 6/8/2025 at approximately 0015, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 4108415 at the ramp facility in Phoenix, reporting potentially undeclared dangerous goods.  The shipment consists of 2 plastic drums.  The drums are marked with "Adhesive 53S" and are prepared in accordance with IATA Regulations, not displaying the required markings, labeling, packaging, or paperwork.  DG Administration was unable to locate a corresponding safety data sheet online for this commodity. The drums are being held for an FAA investigation.

Shipment discovered leaking during sort operations. 33 fiberboard boxes overpacked on a pallet. Inside each box were 6 metal cans @ 3.78 Liters each. 4 boxes were damaged, approx. 6 cans were badly dented and leaking. All remaining contents were placed in a salvage drum and held pending disposition from the shipper.

On June 27, 2025, one (1) 55-gallon drum of adhesive was punctured and released approximately 15-gallons of product to the dock floor. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from First Call Environmental (FCE) to remediate the site. FCE personnel deployed granular absorbent to the concrete floor and worked them in with hand tools, utilizing a cleaning agent with absorbent wipes to collect any residual product. All impacted materials were containerized in one (1) 55-gallon drum. The damaged drum of product was overpacked.

column169: At 09:06 ET, XPO notified the Call Center of a cargo release at terminal XNB. It was reported that approximately 2 gallons of Battery Acid released from two 2050-pound batteries due to falling over while in transit due to being improperly secured. The release impacted trailer #3216309 at dock #56. Call Center reviewed the SDS with the caller and determined that terminal personnel are capable of cleaning the release with PPE available on site, the terminal has requested contractor dispatch.   Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 2-gallons of UN2794 Batteries, wet, filled with Acid to area of the wooden trailer floor due to improper loading. The crew neutralized the trailer floor with an acid eater. The damaged batteries were up righted and secured to a new pallet. The neutralized battery acid impacted absorbents were containerized into a 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal  personnel to manage.

ABF Operation Supervisor states that they were unloading trailer 552622 in dock door 97 when they noticed that a pallet of UN1155, DIETHYL ETHER, 3, PG I was rubbing up against a bulk head with no duntage and resulted in 10 L to spill out onto the trailer. ABF Supervisor states that there was no dun tage was around the shipment to protect it from getting punctured resulting in the spill. Safety advised to close trailer door until CURA arrives on scene. Safety contacted CURA services and they're dispatching a cleanup crew on emergency response to the terminal.

column169: Pkg is considered Undeclared as it is missing required Hazmat markings for shipment containing aerosols. Contents of original pkg repacked in FedEx repack box. Pkg was damaged at the origin terminal and Damaged Package Report (DPR) was filed. Required accompanying documents were not filed. Shipment "Service Code" designates Ltd Qty. Damaged portion (presumably non-hazardous cleaner) was removed from the original packaging and discarded. Remaining contents: laundry detergent, water filtration pitcher and sunscreen (aerosol) were repacked in the oversized FedEx carton with no packing material. Vent cap came off laundry detergent bottle allowing liquid to leak wetting and coating contents. Removal of pkg from sortation and inspection resulted in the discovery of the undeclared aerosol contents.

column169: At 2224 ET, XPO notified ERTS of a cargo release at UPH. It was reported that approximately 10 gallons of Blue Raspberry Base were released from a 10-gallon plastic pail due to improper bracing by terminal BCA. The release impacted trailer # 3193590 at dock door 111. ERTS will proceed to dispatch a contractor to the site to complete cleanup activities.  Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 10-gallons of UN2920 Blue Raspberry Base product released to an 8’ x 4’ area of the wooden trailer floor due to improper loading. The contractors noted there were (5) 10-gallon plastic pails damaged or leaking. They containerized the (5) damaged/leaking pails into (2) 55- gallon poly drums along with PPE and pallet pieces. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

Upon opening the trailer at the disposal facility, it was discovered that part of the load had shifted during transportation. Thirty 5-gallon pails containing lithium scrap soaked in mineral oil had shifted off the pallet and fell over in the nose of the trailer. One of the lids on a 5-gallon pail had loosened up as a result of the load shifting and began to leak. Approximately 0.25 gallons of material was spilled. The spill was contained and cleaned up appropriately. The material was then incinerated later the same day.
column170: A corrective actions meeting was scheduled immediately following the report of the leak to discuss the incident and the corrective measures to be taken to prevent a reoccurrence. In the future, pails should not be double stacked when not banded to the pallet. Containers must be shrink-wrapped to the pallet (properly secured), as well as inspecting containers prior to shipment to ensure all lids are securely on.

column169: At 17:37 ET, XPO notified the Call Center of a cargo release and tote transfer at terminal XDM. It was reported that approximately 40 gallons of Reax Complete released from one 265-gallon tote due to being strapped down. The release impacted trailer #4855008 and asphalt. No storm drains or waterways are reported to be impacted by the release.   Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 100-gallons UN3082 Reax Complete product released to the wooden trailer floor and to the asphalt due to improper loading. The contractors cleaned the spill using granular absorbents and generated (2) 55-gallon metal drums containing the absorbents and (2) 55-gallon poly drums containing the tote and impacted pallets. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column169: At 1330et driver arrived to pick up loaded trailer from drop lot and noticed liquid dripping on to gravel from trailer. The driver the put down absorbent and boobs below trailer to contain and absorb the liquid and called in our response team to come out. The response team arrived @1530et and assessed the situation and began the process of unloading the trailer to get to the container that was leaking. The 250 gallon IBC container was found in front 1/4 of the trailer. They then moved it to the rear and began transferring the remaining liquid into an new container. The solids were then removed and placed into a new container along with the damaged tote that was then cut up to be disposed of properly. The material that had leaked into the trailer and ground was then collected along with the absorbents used to contain the release. The clean up was completed around 2300. The team then returned on 6/23 with equipment to remove any of the gravel that was contaminated and dispose of it properly.
column170: It was discovered that the metal cage around the plastic tote had been damaged and a sharp edge of the cage had rubbed a hole in the side of the tote. Training will be completed on the proper inspection of a container before being accepted for transportation.

Our driver delivered a bulk load of Butyl Cellosolve Solvent to Axalta Coatings in Jacksonville, Texas. The driver used his pump and hoses to offload the shipment from our tank trailer into the customers storage tank. During the unloading process a leak developed due to an undetected cut in one of our discharge hoses and product poured onto the ground. Our driver immediately shut the interval on the trailer contained the spill. The customer then cleaned used an in house crew to clean up the material the was on the ground.   The driver used a different hose and offloaded the rest of the product that was in the trailer.  The hose that failed was previously inspected by our shop and showed no signs of any defects. The hose failed because there was an undetected cut in it. When the driver returned back to the terminal the hose was inspected and discarded. We have spoken to the driver and asked him to make sure that he inspects his hoses more thoroughly.
column170: We inspect our drivers hoses once per quarter and will continue that practice. The hoses are visually inspected and also pressure tested. We have asked the driver to avoid dragging his hoses on the ground and to make sure that they are visually inspected prior to using them. If any defects are found the hose is not to be used.

On June 12, 2025, at 1542 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Landstar Inway personnel in Princeton, IL regarding the release of TRANSCHEM Muriatic Acid. Contractors were dispatched to the site to perform all onsite clean-up activities. Upon arrival, contractors confirmed the release of 1.0 gallon of TRANSCHEM Muriatic Acid (UN1789, 8, II) from (1) 1-gallon plastic jug onto the trailer floor. The release was reportedly due to a load shift causing the jug to be smashed, impacting the trailer floor and 23 cardboard boxes containing (92) 1-gallon jugs of product. The release was cleaned with absorbent pads and the proper PPE. No drains or waterways were impacted by the release. All jugs of product within the impacted cardboard boxes were removed from the boxes and containerized along with the damaged cardboard. All waste generated from addressing this release was containerized in (4) 55-gallon DFs which were taken off-site by the contractor for proper disposal.

column169: Product spill while in transit

Transportation Services Unlimited Inc. (TSU) CMV operator arrived at 03:25am to deliver hypochlorite solutions to customer Pinch A Penny 33's, owned and operated by Kristine and Michael Moureau, two 1800 gallon above ground storage tanks.  This was a routine delivery for the TSU CMV operator, and the TSU CMV operator failed to properly conduct an inspection of the customer's equipment prior to unloading.  Due to this failure, the operator was unaware of the recent installation of the new hypochlorite solutions KemKey connector and the disconnection of the old offloading line. The operator connected his cargo tanker unloading hose to the customer's old offloading line, which was no longer connected to the above ground storage tank.  CMV operator began the unloading operations, after a few minutes the operator noticed that the above ground storage tank was not increasing in the amount of hypochlorite solutions.  It was at this time, the operator investigated the cause and found that the unloading operation through the old offloading line was releasing hypochlorite solutions directly to the ground instead of filling the customer's tank. The operator immediately terminated unloading operations, thus mitigating any further potential spillage. There was no equipment failure.  The hazardous material release was due to the following:  1) the lack of communication to the CMV operator regarding the installation of the new KemKey connector, 2) the failure to remove/render inoperable the old offloading line, and 3) the CMV operator's failure to properly conduct an equipment inspection prior to beginning the unloading process which resulted in the hazardous material release. CBI was contacted to handle the cleanup. https://www.cliffberryinc.com  **** Property owner notified of the hazardous material discharge, and provided a phone number to the National Response Center (NRC). Property owner was notifying the NRC, and the incident/call number was provided to the property owner (not us, so the NRC incident/call number is unknown).****
column170: CMV operator was terminated for violating a number of company policies related to the spill. The company is investigating a better means of communicating mechanical changes made to customer delivery equipment.

ABF stated that while a forklift operator was moving the commodity it had fallen off the skid, resulting in the spill. Following a site assessment, FCE personnel noted approximately 2-quarts released to the trailer interior and pail cardboard container. FCE collected the damaged 1-quart pails and co ntainerized them into one (1) 55-gallon drum for terminal disposal. FCE personnel deployed absorbents, absorbent pads and utilized hand tools to scrape up material. All insulation impacted material was collected and containerized into one (1) 15-gallon pail for future terminal disposal. FCE personne l noted no further actions required on-site and crews demobilized at approximately 9:00 a.m. CDT.~

column169: Over fill

Carrier was operating a rented box truck with a GVWR of 25,999 in interstate commerce. Carrier had purchased 26 drums from NW Auto Solutions of reported Hydrofluoric Acid in 55 gallon plastic drums. Carrier reported they did not have shipping papers for the load.   Carrier was travelling NB on I-205 in Portland when they reported they were cut off in traffic, left the highway, and collided with the trailer of a flat-bed trailer which was stopped on the shoulder. The box truck sidewall was penetrated by the flat-bed, resulting in the damage of one of the drums. The entire contents of the drum leaked out onto the highway, resulting in a complete highway closure.   Initial law enforcement responders reported some airway discomfort. One responded was evaluated at a local ER a day after.  Portland Fire Bureau's Hazmat response team applied absorbent and mitigated the leak. It is unknown if any of the material leaked into the waterway.   Carrier was hauling without a hazmat endorsed CDL, no placards, no shipping papers, and no emergency response information. USDOT inspection was completed and documented under inspection number ORAL41131179.   Carrier was advised to report to NRC. Reported contacted NRC on 6/21/25 and discovered no report was made. Reporter then made report to NRC.
column170: Shipper provide carrier with shipping papers. Carrier placards load and properly trains employees in hazmat response.

column169: A Veolia truck was transporting a roll off box of residual incinerator ash from Veolia, Port Arthur, Texas to the Veolia, Gum Springs, AR landfill for disposal. While travelling around a curve on Highway 26 near the 300 block the vehicle veered out of its designated travel lane and onto the right shoulder. The driver then over corrected to the left, causing the vehicle to overturn onto its right side.   During the incident, the hazardous materials container detached from the vehicle and released its contents onto the roadway, shoulder, and adjacent ditch. In addition, the truck leaked diesel fuel, hydraulic fluid, and other hazardous substances into the ditch.  The Veolia driver was transported to the hospital via ambulance and was released shortly after with minor injuries.
column170: Implement specialized training for truck drivers hauling roll off containers to ensure knowledge and awareness of weight/height distribution and potential hazards of shifting weight or load push when maneuvering curves.   Evaluate improvements for weight distribution of ash boxes while filling at the Veolia, Port Arthur Facility.
